    "privileged_info_summary": "The task uses real data from CAMEO Chemicals (NOAA), a government chemical safety database. The 10.6 eV lamp energy is a standard specification for photoionization detectors in environmental testing. All six chemicals (Benzene, Methane, Carbon tetrachloride, Trichloroethylene, Chloroform, and Styrene) and their CAS numbers are correctly identified. One metadata error was found: chloroform's ionization energy is listed as 11.37 eV but CAMEO Chemicals/NIOSH 2024 data shows it as 11.42 eV. All detectable/not-detectable classifications are correct based on the 10.6 eV threshold. Three chemicals are detectable (Benzene 9.24 eV, Trichloroethylene 9.45 eV, Styrene 8.40 eV) and three are not (Methane 12.61 eV, Carbon tetrachloride 11.47 eV, Chloroform 11.42 eV).",
